      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling an SMSF Property in Queensland: What Trustees Need to Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        An SMSF property sale is not the same as a personal property sale. The rules around who can buy, how tax is applied, and what happens to the proceeds are specific to the superannuation environment. Here is what Queensland trustees need to understand before proceeding.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Self-managed superannuation funds hold a significant portion of Queensland's investment property market. When it comes time to sell one of those properties, many trustees discover that the transaction involves layers of compliance and coordination that a standard residential sale does not. The contract is signed by the trustees on behalf of the fund, the proceeds flow into the fund's bank account rather than a personal account, and what happens next is governed by superannuation law rather than property law alone. Getting the process right requires your SMSF accountant, your property solicitor, and in most cases your financial adviser all working from the same understanding of the transaction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What it means to hold property inside an SMSF</h2>
      <p>An SMSF holds property as an investment asset of the fund. The property is owned not by the individual members but by the trustees in their capacity as trustees of the fund (or by a corporate trustee on behalf of the fund). This distinction matters at every stage of the sale: the contract is executed by the trustees in that capacity, settlement proceeds are paid to the fund's bank account, and the gain or loss on sale is a fund-level tax event rather than a personal one.</p>

      <p>The sole purpose test under the Superannuation Industry (Supervision) Act 1993 requires that all fund assets, including property, be held for the purpose of providing retirement benefits to members. This is relevant at sale because the question of who the fund can sell to, and what can be done with the proceeds, is constrained by that overriding obligation. A sale that benefits a member or related party directly, rather than the fund, risks breaching the sole purpose test and triggering penalties including the fund losing its complying status.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who can buy an SMSF property: the related party rules</h2>
      <p>The related party rules under the SIS Act are one of the most important constraints on an SMSF property sale. As a general rule, SMSF property cannot be sold to a member of the fund or to a related party, which includes the member's spouse, children, business partners, and associated entities. This rule applies regardless of whether the sale is at market value.</p>

      <p>There is one significant exception: business real property. Commercial property that is used wholly and exclusively in the carrying on of a business can generally be sold to a related party at market value, provided the transaction is on arm's-length terms. Residential property does not qualify for this exception. A member who has been living in a property held inside their SMSF would be breaching the rules on multiple fronts and cannot purchase that property from the fund at any price.</p>

      <p>For most Queensland SMSF trustees selling residential investment property, this means the property must be sold to an unrelated third party through the normal market. There is no shortcut that allows the property to transfer to a member for personal use, even at the end of the fund's life or after a member retires.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tax on the capital gain: pension phase versus accumulation phase</h2>
      <p>One of the significant advantages of selling property inside an SMSF is the potential tax treatment of the capital gain. The applicable rate depends on the phase the fund is in at the time of sale.</p>

      <p>If the fund is fully in pension phase at the time of sale, meaning all member balances are supporting account-based pensions, the capital gain on the property is entirely tax-free. This is one of the most compelling reasons SMSF trustees time their property sales to coincide with the pension phase of their fund. A large capital gain on a property that would attract significant CGT in a personal name can pass through the fund without any tax liability when the fund is in pension phase.</p>

      <p>If the fund is in accumulation phase and the property has been held for more than 12 months, the net capital gain is taxed at 10% at the fund level. This is the concessional CGT rate available to complying funds under the Income Tax Assessment Act. If the property has been held for less than 12 months, the standard fund tax rate of 15% applies to the full gain. For most long-held investment properties, the 12-month threshold is not an issue, but it is worth confirming the acquisition date carefully, particularly if the property was transferred into the fund rather than purchased directly.</p>

      <p>The tax is paid by the fund, not by individual members. It reduces the net amount credited to member balances after the sale, but it does not create a personal tax liability for the trustees or members.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens to an LRBA loan when the property is sold</h2>
      <p>Many SMSF properties in Queensland were purchased using a limited recourse borrowing arrangement (LRBA), which is the only permitted form of borrowing available to SMSFs under superannuation law. Under an LRBA, the fund takes out a loan to acquire an asset, and the asset is held in a separate bare trust until the loan is repaid. The lender's recourse in the event of default is limited to the specific asset held in the bare trust, not to the rest of the fund's assets.</p>

      <p>When an SMSF property purchased under an LRBA is sold, the loan must be discharged from the sale proceeds before any net amount is credited to the SMSF. The bare trust is unwound as part of settlement, the security is released, and the remaining proceeds flow into the fund's bank account. Your property solicitor needs to be aware that the title is held in a bare trust structure rather than directly by the trustee, because it affects how the contract is executed and how settlement is managed with the lender's solicitor.</p>

      <p>Trustees should obtain a loan payout figure from the lender before contracts are exchanged, so they can confirm the net proceeds that will remain in the fund after discharge. A property that has appreciated significantly will generate a healthy fund balance after LRBA repayment. A property that has not appreciated as expected may produce modest net proceeds once the loan is repaid, particularly if the LRBA balance has not reduced significantly through principal payments.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the proceeds must be used for</h2>
      <p>Once the net sale proceeds are credited to the SMSF's bank account, they must remain inside the fund. They cannot be distributed to members as cash unless a member has met a condition of release under superannuation law. Conditions of release include reaching preservation age and retiring, reaching age 65, or in limited circumstances, other qualifying events such as permanent incapacity or terminal illness.</p>

      <p>Trustees who sell a property and assume they can access the proceeds personally, because the property was the fund's main asset or because they plan to wind up the fund, need to understand that the distribution of fund assets to members requires the fund to be in a position to pay benefits, which means members must have met conditions of release. If no member has met a condition of release, the proceeds must be reinvested inside the fund or held in the fund's bank account until a condition is met.</p>

      <p>If trustees are selling the property as part of a strategy to wind up the fund and move to a retail or industry super fund, the process involves rolling the remaining fund balance out to the receiving fund rather than distributing cash directly to members. The trustee's accountant will manage this process as part of the fund wind-up.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The specialists you need and what each one does</h2>
      <p>An SMSF property sale requires three distinct professionals, and a problem that arises from any of them can affect the others. Understanding who is responsible for what will prevent gaps.</p>

      <p>Your SMSF accountant is responsible for the fund's tax position: calculating the capital gain, advising on whether the fund qualifies for pension-phase tax treatment, ensuring the fund's financial records are updated after settlement, and preparing the fund's annual return. They should be engaged before the property is listed, not after contracts are exchanged, because the timing of the sale relative to the fund's phase can significantly affect the tax outcome.</p>

      <p>Your property solicitor prepares and reviews the contract of sale, manages the settlement process, deals with the bare trust documentation if an LRBA is involved, and ensures the contract reflects that the vendor is the trustee of the fund rather than an individual. They also communicate with the lender's solicitor on LRBA discharge. Using a solicitor who is familiar with SMSF transactions is worth the additional cost for the reduced risk of a documentation error that delays settlement.</p>

      <p>Your financial adviser provides strategic guidance on whether selling is consistent with the fund's investment strategy, what to do with the proceeds after settlement, and whether the timing is optimal given the members' retirement plans and the fund's phase. The adviser's input is most valuable in the planning stage, before the decision to sell is finalised, because there may be alternatives worth considering.</p>

